Detailed Description

Extensions to support explicit AI Engine system-wide programming in C++.

427#ifdef TRISYCL_DEBUG

429#endif
430 TRISYCL_DUMP_T("axi_stream_switch " << this
431 << " (" << x_coordinate << ',' << y_coordinate

433 // If the port comes from the FIFO, use a FIFO-featured
434 // router_minion instead

437 /* A special AXI switch routing interface which provides a
438 FIFO. Since a router_minion has already some internal FIFO
439 behavior, some deeper FIFO behavior can actually be
440 implemented with a specific router_minion with a deeper
441 FIFO internally, to avoid having 2 active components, the
442 FIFO + the router_minion */

451 // "FIFO" can be just directly connected to this specific

454 axi_ss_geo::s_fifo_range))

◆ translate_port

template<typename AXIStreamGeography >
static auto trisycl::vendor::xilinx::acap::aie::axi_stream_switch< AXIStreamGeography >::translate_port
inlinestatic
Initial value:
= [] (int user_port,
auto physical_port_min,
auto physical_port_max,
const auto& error_message) {
auto port_min = static_cast<int>(physical_port_min);
auto port_max = static_cast<int>(physical_port_max);
auto last_user_port = port_max - port_min;
if (user_port < 0 || user_port > last_user_port)
throw ::trisycl::runtime_error {
(boost::format {
"%1%: %2% is not a valid port number between 0 and %3%" }
% error_message % user_port % last_user_port).str() };
return static_cast<decltype(physical_port_min)>(port_min + user_port);
}

Validate the user port number and translate it to the physical port number.

Parameters
[in]user_portis the logical port number, starting to 0
[in]physical_port_minis the physical lower port number to map to
[in]physical_port_maxis the physical higher port number to map to
Exceptions
trisycl::runtime_errorif the port number is invalid
Returns
the physical port number in the switch corresponding to the logical port
Todo:
This makes sense only for core tile

◆ trisycl::vendor::xilinx::acap::aie::cascade_stream

struct trisycl::vendor::xilinx::acap::aie::cascade_stream
template<typename Geography>
struct trisycl::vendor::xilinx::acap::aie::cascade_stream< Geography >

Implementation of the cascade stream infrastructure between AI Engine tiles.

Based on Math Engine (ME) Architecture Specification, Revision v2.01

March 2019

3.5.4 Data Movement using Cascade Streams, p. 93

2.14 Device-level Floorplanning Guidelines, 2.14.2 Array Edges, p. 69

4.4 ME Core Interfaces, 4.4.4 Cascade Stream Interface, p. 120 explains there is a FIFO depth of 4

5.9.3.6 Cascade Streams: explains that there are only blocking accesses

Direct stream interface: One cascade stream in, one cascade stream out (384-bits)

Todo:
Remove this global infrastructure and distribute it on the tile_infrastructure itself

◆ trisycl::vendor::xilinx::acap::aie::dma_dsl

class trisycl::vendor::xilinx::acap::aie::dma_dsl
template<typename Tile, typename DMA, typename LockRef = bool>
class trisycl::vendor::xilinx::acap::aie::dma_dsl< Tile, DMA, LockRef >

Implement a small DSL to chain DMA & locking operations like allowed by the hardware.

Parameters
[in]Tileis the type of tile to keep a reference on it
[in]DMAis the type of the DMA involved in the operation
[in]LockRefis the type of the reference to the lock once a lock() operation is involved. Otherwise just use a bool as a dummy type internally.

◆ trisycl::vendor::xilinx::acap::aie::memory

struct trisycl::vendor::xilinx::acap::aie::memory
template<typename AIE, int X, int Y>
struct trisycl::vendor::xilinx::acap::aie::memory< AIE, X, Y >

The AI Engine Memory Module infrastructure of a tile.

This is the type you need to inherit from to define the content of a CGRA tile memory module.

Parameters
AIEis the type representing the full CGRA with the programs and memory contents
Xis the horizontal coordinate of the memory module
Yis the vertical coordinate of the memory module

◆ trisycl::vendor::xilinx::acap::aie::program

struct trisycl::vendor::xilinx::acap::aie::program
template<typename AIEDevice, template< typename AIE, int X, int Y > typename Tile = acap::aie::tile, template< typename AIE, int X, int Y > typename Memory = acap::aie::memory>
struct trisycl::vendor::xilinx::acap::aie::program< AIEDevice, Tile, Memory >

Define an AI Engine CGRA program with its code and memory per core.

Parameters
AIEDeviceis the device description of the machine to instantiate with the physical size
Tileis the description of the program tiles to instantiate. By default each tile will run an empty program.
Memoryis the description of the machine memory modules. By default the machine has empty memory modules.

Launch the programs of all the tiles of the CGRA in their own executor (CPU thread, fiber...) and wait for their completion.

225 {
226 // Start each tile program in its own executor
227 boost::hana::for_each(tiles, [&] (auto& t) {
228 t.single_task([&] {
229 TRISYCL_DUMP_T("Starting AIE tile (" << t.x << ',' << t.y
230 << ") linear id = " << t.linear_id());
231 /* Just use a capture by reference in the following
232 because there is direct execution here */
233 auto kernel = [&] {
234 // If the tile has an operator(), use it
235 if constexpr (requires { t(); })
236 return [&] { t(); };
237 /* Else the kernel should have a run
238 member function and use it. */
239 else
240 return [&] { t.run(); };
241 }();
242 using kernel_type = decltype(kernel);
243 // Use the kernel type as its SYCL name too
244 kernel_outliner<kernel_type, kernel_type>(kernel);
245 TRISYCL_DUMP_T("Stopping AIE tile (" << t.x << ',' << t.y << ')');

◆ trisycl::vendor::xilinx::acap::aie::tile

struct trisycl::vendor::xilinx::acap::aie::tile
template<typename AIE_Program, int X, int Y>
struct trisycl::vendor::xilinx::acap::aie::tile< AIE_Program, X, Y >

The AI Engine tile infrastructure defining the program of a tile.

This is the type you need to inherit from to define the program of a CGRA tile.

Parameters
AIE_Programis the type representing the full CGRA with the programs and memory contents
Xis the horizontal coordinate of the memory module
Yis the vertical coordinate of the memory module
Todo:
(Andrew Gozillon) FYI, until Intel fix the way they handle base classes in the SYCL compiler frontend this tile_base can never have non-default constructed data (on the device side implementation, the host should be fine to have whatever). As the hack I have in place just now only outlines a call to the base classes default constructor, it might be feasible to work around that though by calling a base class "fill" function in the tile constructor or tweaking the way the run function of a tile is outlined so that it outlines it as a copy of the full object rather than components of the object and reconstructing it inside the kernel (although you'll fall into the standard layout trap as you'll be passing a full object to the kernel invocation and it'd take some reworking of the Tile's main generation).

A proper fix for this is probably quite difficult as you'd need to take into account the base classes dependencies among-st other things like the constructor body not being available in the same TU, some discussion here: https://github.com/intel/llvm/issues/488

359 {
360 if constexpr (y & 1) {
361 // Propagate a token from West to East and back
362 if constexpr (!is_west_column()) {
363 // Wait for the Western neighbour to be ready
364 mem().lock(lock).acquire_with_value(true);

inline

Get the memory module relative to the tile.

Parameters
[in]Dxis the horizontal offset relative to the current core tile
[in]Dyis the vertical offset relative to the current core tile
Returns
the memory tile object

Note that since a core tile has a 4-neighbor connectivity, at least one of the offset needs to be 0 and the other to be either 1 or -1.

The AI Engine tile infrastructure common to all the tiles.

Launch a callable on this tile.

◆ trisycl::vendor::xilinx::acap::aie::detail::tile_infrastructure

class trisycl::vendor::xilinx::acap::aie::detail::tile_infrastructure
template<typename Geography>
class trisycl::vendor::xilinx::acap::aie::detail::tile_infrastructure< Geography >

The AI Engine tile infrastructure common to all the tiles.

This allows some type erasure while accessing the common tile infrastructure.

Parameters
AIEis the type representing the full CGRA with the programs and memory contents
